\section*{Introduction}
% Paragraph 1
% emw5Jul -- I feel like unless you are making a very controversial point, you only need max 3 refs ever (I would pick one older -- meaning 2000s -- classic and a recent IPCC personally), so cut down here -- also, how can an article from 1974 support this statement below about ACC? ... Fix this THROUGHOUT. If you really want to have a lot, then have 4 max methinks. 
The most frequently observed biological impact of climate change is shifts in phenology---the timing of recurring life history events \citep{parmesan_poleward_1999, menzel_european_2006, calvin_ipcc_2023}. Across many plant species, spring events have advanced \citep{wolfe_climate_2005,chmielewski_response_2001,fu_recent_2014}, while autumn events have delayed---but to a much lesser extent \citep{gallinat_autumn_2015,jeong_macroscale_2014}. Together, early springs and later autumns lengthen the growing season (GS), which should increase growth for many species, including trees \citep{keenan_net_2014, stridbeck_partly_2022}. \\

% Paragraph 2
% emw5Jul -- precision and accuracy are different; you mean accurate here and you should memorize this difference
The positive relationship between growing season length and tree growth is important for accurate climate models because of the role of trees in mitigating emissions. Carbon sequestration by forests is an important process in climate models \citep{friedlingstein_global_2026}.
% emw5Jul -- you need a sentence right here that says (with refs and correct which noun you -- growth or storage or something else -- goes best): With warming, research has repeatedly found a connection between longer seasons and increased growth/carbon storage (REFS). 
Temperate forests offset roughly 47\% of the global carbon sink, diminishing the consequences of human-emitted greenhouse gas emissions on the climate \citep{harrisGlobalMapsTwentyfirst2021}. The future of this net carbon sink by temperate forests relies on the assumption that longer and warmer seasons will keep increasing carbon storage by trees \citep{pan_enduring_2024}. However, a shift in this relationship could impact the future of this critical carbon sink. \\ 

% Paragraph 3
% emw5Jul -- 'Indeed' does not work here for me. 
New studies suggest that longer GS do not always increase growth \citep{dow_warm_2022,silvestro_longer_2023,matula_shifts_2023,charletdesauvage_temperature_2022,cabon_crossbiome_2022}.  Recently, \cite{dow_warm_2022} found that warmer springs lengthened the growing season, but did not increase the peak growth rate or total annual growth in two temperate forest communities. Working across biomes, \cite{cabon_crossbiome_2022} found a similar trend, where the gross primary production and growth appeared decoupled. However, neither of these studies could clearly establish why they found no relationship while previous studies have.
% emw5Jul -- make sure it flows to the next sentence (which you may then need to adjust). 
Understanding whether temperate forests will keep being a net carbon sink requires answering why trees do not grow more despite longer GS. \\

% Paragraph 4
% emw5Jul -- add a ref below before next time I see this.
A longer GS does not necessarily mean more favorable thermal conditions for growth. First, longer seasons are not necessarily warmer (REF). While the well-documented advance of spring phenology elongates the GS \citep{keenan_net_2014}, spring days are short and usually cool (Figure \ref{fig:GSfig}a). Therefore, this advance may contribute little to a tree's annual growing degree days (GDD) accumulation (Figure \ref{fig:GSfig}b). In contrast, even small shifts to later end of season events can lead to larger changes in annual GDD; since much more GDD accumulates per day during this period any extra end of season (EOS) days may be more important than start of season \citep[SOS][]{buonaiuto_early_2026}.  \\

% emw5Jul -- start a new paragraph here and be a bit easier on your reader -- you're making contrasting statement here without acknowledging it for the reader; you just said later seasons EOS is important than you suggest 'water availability may become insufficient to support continuous growth throughout the GS' -- see edits below. 
Other factors beyond the thermal season may affect whether longer seasons increase growth. While trees may have a longer period to grow, water availability may become insufficient to support continuous growth throughout the GS \citep{wang_seasonal_2025}. Competition for light and nutrients may further limit the capacity of trees to benefit from longer seasons, especially for the ones positioned below the forest canopy \citep{cleland_effects_2024,augspurger_differences_2003,sweeneyComparisonTimingSpring2024}. Additionally, trees may have internal constraints that prevent them from increasing growth with longer seasons. Growth like other biological processes is under strict genetic control. Thus, even with optimal environmental conditions, physiological constraints may prevent temperate trees from growing indefinitely \citep{korner_four_2023,wolkovich_why_2025}, but we currently have a limited understanding of how well tree phenology can track changing conditions. \\
% emw5Jul -- above, you don't really mean 'all these factors' since competition and water won't so much affect phenology, so see my edits below. 

% Paragraph 5
Current research suggests that leaf and wood phenology differ in their plasticity in response to changing environmental conditions across species and life stages [*REF]. Leaf phenology (e.g. leafout) in the spring is a highly plastic trait and is very responsive to temperature, while end of season phenology (e.g. budset) is much less plastic and mostly driven by photoperiod \citep{baumgarten_indeterminacy_2026}. Additionally, leaf phenology and growth are closely synchronized in diffuse-porous species (e.g. \textit{Betula}), making leaf phenology a good proxy for setting the start and end of the GS in such species \citep{marchand_timing_2021,silvestro_roots_2025,suzuki_phenological_1996}. % emw5Jul -- are they less synchronized in ring porous? You write above that 'leaf and wood phenology differ in their plasticity' but you do not back that up in this paragraph ... I think you should change the topic sentence to: Current research suggests that leaf and wood phenology differ in their plasticity in response to changing environmental conditions across species and life stages (I would go with this sentence!). 
While this proxy is useful for setting the boundaries of the GS, it does not indicate how much trees grow annually. How flexible growth is in response to changing GS length and conditions varies between species, and may also differ with tree age, with juvenile trees being generally ... % emw5Jul -- more responsive I think? Finish the sentence, I moved it up since it felt massively tacked on below. 
This relationship may also vary also below the species-level, across populations \citep{baumgarten_indeterminacy_2026,way_photoperiod_2015}. \\

% Paragraph 6
% emw5Jul -- you just talked about 'changing environmental conditions' and now you write 'abiotic conditions' -- I don't see how these are different so you're just confusing your reader with the new term. So I just cut it. 
Local adaptation could limit tree growth responses of different populations with future climate \citep{soolanayakanahally_timing_2013,wolkovich_why_2025}. Trees from northern provenances will likely grow less with longer seasons, because they have adapted to shorter seasons \citep{aitken_time_2016,way_photoperiod_2015}. Additionally, budset (EOS event) is known to be strongly locally adapted while leafout (SOS event) is not \citep{zeng_weak_2024}, which likely explains why shifts in SOS with warming have been so much greater than shifts in EOS. 
% emw5Jul -- I am not 100% sure what you're trying to say below ... Maybe you just mean: Longer seasons may thus be driven by earlier SOS, when thermal conditions are less favorable, and little change in EOS when thermal conditions are more favorable, limited any increases in growth ... Or: This predicts a latitudinal gradient in growth responses, with more limited responses in northern populations where EOS is constrained to earlier. ????
This hints towards the EOS as a bigger constraining factor than SOS for tree growth potential across a latitudinal gradient. Thus, common gardens investigating the effect of provenance latitude could  help predict how climate change will affect tree growth. \\

% Paragraph 7 (I cut 8) 
To understand the relationship between GS and growth, we need to understand how growth varies across species and populations while disentangling how much longer seasons are also more thermally favorable seasons. We aim to address this by studying how growth and GS relate across species, populations and multiple metrics of GS length. Working with juvenile trees sourced from four populations and grown in one common garden, we examine how growth, measured via tree rings, and leaf phenology covary over three years. We consider effects of both the length of the season (i.e. number of growing days in the season) and its thermal conditions (i.e. GDD accumulated in the season). 

