\section*{Results}
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Info
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Our dataset comprised four deciduous tree species from four sites with leaf phenology data spanning three years (2018 to 2020) for a total of \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations, yielding 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)} complete growing seasons (GS) for 
\Sexpr{length(unique(emp$treeid))} individuals. At the common garden location, the mean summer temperature was similar across years with 2019 being the coolest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2019)]}$^\circ$C), 2020 the hottest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2020)]}$^\circ$C), and 2018 in between 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2018)]}$^\circ$C). There was no drought for those three years, except for in 2020, where a moderate summer drought (June-August) ramped up to a severe drought in September \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026}.
The calendar and thermal seasons ranged from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$pgsGSL)} days and 
\Sexpr{round(min(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGSL)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$pgsGSL)} days and \Sexpr{round(max(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ainc} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGSL)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}a and b). 
The earliest leafout was
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.min(emp$leafout)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}) and the latest,
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.max(emp$leafout)]} (also {\Ainc}, but in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$leafout)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}c). The earliest budset was 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.min(emp$budset)]} ({\Ball} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]}) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.max(emp$budset)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$budset)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotPred}d. Finally, annual ring widths across years varied from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$lengthMM)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Bpop} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$lengthMM)]}; Figure \ref{fig:wcboxplotRW}).  \\


