Longer growing seasons increased growth for all species, but varied depending on the metric used to measure it. We report estimates as means and 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI) that correspond to ring width change in mm on the log scale---henceforth `\RW per days'  or `\RW per GDD,' with days and GDD being adjusted to represent more meaningful units, as described above (see `Data analyses' section in Methods for more details).
Warmer thermal seasons increased growth for Paper birch (\textit{Betula papyrifera}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]} \RW scaled GDD), Grey birch (\textit{Betula populifolia}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]} \RW scaled GDD), and Yellow birch (\textit{Betula alleghaniensis}; $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} \RW scaled GDD), grey alder (\textit{Alnus incana}) trended in the same direction
($\beta =$ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$mean[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p5[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gdd$p95[which(bspp_df2_gdd$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]} \RW scaled GDD); Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}a and e; Table\ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).
