\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])},
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "A. incana")])} \RW scaled GSL). {\Bpap} also grew more with longer calendar seasons
($\beta =$ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]} \RW scaled GSL), while the other two \textit{Betula} did not, though they trended in the same way ({\Ball}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI: 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} \RW scaled GSL, and {\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$mean[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, UI: 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$p95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]} \RW scaled GSL; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}b and f; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). 
On a scaled axis \citep[through $z$-scoring,][]{gelman_data_2006}, the thermal and calendar season were similarly predictive (Figure \ref{fig:bsppZscored}). Results with basal area increment (BAI) for the GDD model were similar to ring width (see Table \ref{tab:BAItab}). \\


%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Question 2
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Increased growth with longer seasons is often presumed to come from growth in the spring, since spring phenology has shifted much more than fall phenology. In contrast to this expectation, we found most species grew more with a later end of season, and only one species grew more with an earlier start of season ({\Ainc} (one of the two species that a longer calendar season increased growth for) $\beta =$
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]} \RW scaled SOS; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). {\Ball} which did not grow more with longer calendar season, grew less with an earlier start of season ($\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, UI:
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])}, 
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")])} \RW scaled SOS; Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g; Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table})---but more with a later end of season ($\beta =$ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, UI:
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]} \RW scaled EOS). Alongside {\Ball}, two other species grew more with a later end of season ({\Bpop}: $\beta =$
\Sexpr{sprintf("%.2f", bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")])}, UI:
