% DISCUSSION
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\clearpage
\section*{Discussion}
Here we used 81 juvenile trees of four species from four provenances to study how longer growing seasons affect tree growth (using annual growth via tree rings and leaf phenology as a proxy for the start and end of season, SOS and EOS, respectively). Longer GS increased growth for all species, but varied on the season metric used to measure it. We found that the thermal season (GDD) was a better predictor for growth than the calendar season (GSL) with no clear impact of provenance.

% \subsection*{The thermal season better predicts growth than the calendar season}
% emw5Jul --  this header breaks up the flow and seems unnecessary to me. You usually connect the results a little earlier than in the middle of the paragraph, so see changes below. Also, please check this paragraph for flow and repetitiveness.... I am not sure if I fully fixed this but you say the same thing often twice (or, across these two paragraph, you say some things 5X!) in a row. 
Our results support the idea that the thermal season is be a better predictor for growth \citep{chuine_processbased_2017,wang_simulation_1998}.  By accounting for differences in daily temperatures, the thermal season may be more closely aligned to when and how fast each day plants can grow compared to the calendar season, which assumes a stable influence of each day on growth. Thus, the short and cool spring days early in the season count for less in the thermal season than the calendar season \citep{buonaiuto_early_2026}. Further supporting this, when we disentangled the calendar season by using the SOS and EOS separately, we found a larger response of growth to EOS, with little effect of SOS. \\

The finding that EOS appears more related to growth than SOS is aligned with previous studies \citep[e.g.,][]{dow_warm_2022,gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,wheeler_snow_2016}, and has important implications. It suggests that studies that solely focus on the SOS (REFS?) could miss when longer seasons lead to more growth, and also that the strong focus on SOS in phenology research may ignore the most important part of the season for growth (REFS). While studies have long called for more research on EOS (cite Gallinat and others), our results suggest we may especially need more work that monitors how growth and phenology shift across the season (Cite Zohner and Zani papers here I think). More studies using fine temporal scale dendrometers and/or xylogenesis could confirm if most growth occurs closer to EOS versus SOS. To date... 
% emw5Jul -- what do studies find so far? Check Zweifel and others... I would then end on how we need these type of data ACROSS species also ... and make it flow to the follow paragraph which I have moved up... 
 \\
% emw5Jul -- you don't actually test for differences BETWEEN species, so you need to be careful in how you phrase everything in this paragraph; it's not bad but  I would rewrite as... 
Our results suggest different growth strategies between species may yield different responses to longer seasons. Our most ruderal species, {\Ainc} was the only species to grow more with a longer calendar season and an earlier SOS. This suggests that species with more ruderal, flexible life-history strategies may actually take advantage of growing more in the spring despite cooler, shorter days  \citep{bowmanEcology2023,furlow_alnus_1997,grime_evidence_1977}. 
% emw5Jul -- now re-write the below to introduce the strategy with the result not AFTER the result ... see above, how I introduced alninc as ruderal before stating its response. 
In contrast, {\Bpap} and {\Bpop} were most driven by the EOS, suggesting that they are both reactive to these late season days characterized by warmer temperatures \citep{burns_silvics_1990}. {\Bpap} juveniles can specifically grow for a long time provided appropriate conditions \citep{burns_silvics_1990}, thus explaining this positive growth response to a later EOS. Lastly, {\Ball} which responded to both the SOS and the EOS points towards a neutralizing % emw5Jul -- counter interacting isn't really a term ... 
trend where an early SOS decreases growth, but a later EOS increases it, muting this species' response to a longer calendar season. \\

Studies including an even wider span of growth strategies across species may find further differences. Our four study species are all relatively fast growing, which should allow them to track changing conditions better than their slower growing counterparts. While we found an overall positive trend of warmer seasons on growth, this might have changed if we used 
% emw5Jul -- fix ()() below, use \citep[][]{}
slower growing species, such as \citep[\textit{Quercus};][]{burns_silvics_1990}. \\
 
% emw5Jul -- you can say a little more here. You should say if the other studies that find this are on juvenile trees, if not, I would have the second sentence here be: while other studies on mature trees have found the same result, our results may have been more muted if the trees were grown in a forest setting. We grew trees in a common garden setting with potentially more space between trees [here give this distance -- it was actually not much! I would estimate maybe 2 m... ask Dan and Cat!] without any shade cloth on tree species. Then, add your ... However, if these trees ... 
Additionally, we used juvenile trees which tend to be more reactive and could in part explain why they grew more with warmer seasons \citep{augspurger_differences_2003,sweeneyComparisonTimingSpring2024}. However, if these trees grew in nature in a mature forest they would have been below the canopy, competing for light and other resources and thus might not have responded as much as we observed in our competition-limited conditions \citep{polgar_leafout_2011}. \\

% emw5Jul -- I would actually then have a short paragraph on the relevance of these findings for how forests may regrow ... 
Our focus on juvenile trees may suggest how forests regrow with the longer warmer seasons of anthropogenic climate change. 
While many plant phenology studies find invasive species appear more responsive to spring warming (CITES, lots by me here so should be easy) these studies are often on herbaceous species. Our results thus suggest more studies of how later season events affect invasions could be especially important for understanding woody plant invasions. Further, the contrasting responses we found across species suggest assembly of native species may depend on growth strategies at both the start and end of the season. 

Our results also suggest assembly models may need less of a focus on population-level differences than previously suggested (CITES). While studies of large latitudinal gradients (CITES) have found lower growth in tree species from poleward latitudes, we found no differences in growth across a latitudinal gradient of 3.5 (ADDdegree) C. Thus, at least across this latitudinal range, local adaption on growth appears weak. Supporting this, we found no evidence of shifting EOS across provenances, despite decades of work finding that EOS events, such as budset, are usually more locally adapted than SOS events such as leafout \citep{zeng_weak_2024}. Yet, a study of the same common garden including all tree and shrub species found EOS appeared to vary strongly by year and shift earlier with earlier SOS \citep{buonaiuto_early_2026}, suggesting EOS may be more variable than currently suggested (CITES). Taken together these results suggest our current understanding of budset being strongly locally adapted and thus varying little with temperature or SOS need more study.

\subsection*{Implications for models and other regions} % emw5Jul -- this subheader does not match the below .. I just changed it but you probably could also just cut it. 

Using a rarely available dataset of tree growth coupled with leaf phenology SOS and EOS, we found an overall positive response from our trees to longer seasons, which has important implications for models of forest assembly, as discussed above, and and also models of future carbon storage. 
% emw5Jul -- I would re-work the below a little, something more like: We found that SOS and EOS asymmetrically matter to growth, which means that how we model these in vegetation and related earth system models may be critical for accurate predictions. [If you know anything about these models you could add it here, for example, do they model SOS as super variable and EOS as photoperiod controlled? Then flow from that if you can ... If you cannot figure out it just skip it for now.] To get EOS right means we need more studies, especially on more species across a larger gradient. This could help tease out whether local adaptation of EOS depends on the species, latitudinal range (both distance and how far north provenances come from) or some combination of the two, which could then feed into improve models. 
Our findings suggest that the SOS and EOS asymmetrically matter to growth, which we explained by differences in temperatures at the boundaries of the GS. Hence, we highlight the importance of considering different metrics of season length and not only SOS \citep[e.g.,][]{dow_warm_2022,gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,wheeler_snow_2016}. 
Finally, we showed strong species differences despite them being closely related. Species differences matter and it is important to include them in carbon model and range shifts projections.

% emw5Jul -- do not 'note' things -- just write them down. You can always delete 'we note that' ...
% emw5Jul --  you just mentioned the below above, why are you mentioning it again (also, I specifically moved this from the last part of the conclusions, so why has it re-appeared?)  ... I am also not sure why you keep on discounting your result due to juvenile trees when you say above other studies found it. Unless ALL these studies are on juvenile trees I am confused by your repeated mentioning of this as a negative... 
% We note that in nature, the positive growth response of juvenile trees may be muted by light competition given their position below the canopy. 

% emw5Jul -- I moved this down, I don't love it here, but it really did not flow above and I think it's okay to end on. 
Integrating our results into models will also require considering how environmental conditions beyond temperature shift across the season, especially soil moisture \citep{gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,li_widespread_2023}. Trees in our common garden were regularly watered, likely relieving any major drought pressures \citep[though studies beyond ours have found a connection between later EOS and more growth, see][]{gaoEarlierStartThermal2022,wang_seasonal_2025}. For the four species we studied, there are currently no increases in drought occurrence within their ranges \citep{nationalcentersforenvironmentalinformationncei_north_2026,agel_drought_2025}, suggesting that growth may increase with longer and warmer GS \citep{agel_drought_2025}, as we found. However, the positive effect of a later EOS could be offset if soil moisture becomes inadequate for growth, and certainly other temperate regions with decreased soil moisture have reported declines in tree growth \citep[e.g.,][]{chiang_evidence_2021,spinoni_will_2018}.
% emw5Jul -- add somethig about how better models will need to integrate over drivers and species or some summing it up sentence. 





